nder of enduring religious pluralism, not least in view of the high prominence given to Islamic experience in arguments against over-generalised notions of secularisation. On the other hand, it explores the question of Christian motivated extremism and religious nationalism. Against this background, the contributors discuss the role of religion in other countries throughout the worldincluding China, Japan, Russia and the MENA region.Debates on religion and politics have, to a high degree, focused on contrasts between Europe and other parts of the world; the long-established assumption that modern societies are on a secularising path seemed have a stronger claim to validity in Europe than elsewhere. This book shows that, if European modernity does represent an exit from religion, this historical process and its implications are still very imperfectly understood.Find Out MoreNotes on the contributors"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aReligion and politics. 0aReligion and politics; Europe. 4aPolitics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aArnason, Johann P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCady, Linell E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaynes, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurd, Elizabeth Shakman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuergensmeyer, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarolewski, Ireneusz Pawel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKarolewski, Ireneusz Paweł, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaya, Ayhan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLagerwey, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat